Best_Course_Features:
Out of all online courses that I've enrolled and completed, this course is one of the most organised courses ever - in terms of resources, structure and announcements. Educational resources are grouped very clearly, it is easy to understand what content we need to focus on each week and what's coming up. The slides are also released at the start of the week, giving us enough time to study and go through material during the week before we complete the quiz and discussion question.
It makes the course much more manageable and enjoyable to complete.
Multiple lecturers also gives us the opportunity from learn from various professionals.
All online courses should adopt a similar structure, because it allows the student to study to their fullest potential.
Course_Improvements: More info on lecture slides, so that when we review lectures, we don't HAVE to listen to the recording. Other than that, this course is great.
BF: Multiple lecturers mean we can benefit from the knowledge of professionals with various experiences.
IM: continuing to do what they're doing!

Best_Course_Features: Steve Most putting the effort in the creating high quality lectures.
Course_Improvements:
there is zero consideration for spaced repetition systems.  SRS pairs nicely with active recall (testing effect) and would be valuable for student learning.

I suggest that the psych faculty look into Anki SRS software to improve learning outcomes.
BF: Brilliant lecturing styles, very energetic and thoughtful of pedagogy. University would feel much more value-for-money with content like his. Often there are youtube videos out there that explain topics way better than any lecturer at Uni. Steve feels like a refreshing exception to that where he wants to be up there with the best explainers.
IM:
Learn what Anki is and how it works, and mention it in your future lectures when talking about memory/active recall/studying etc.
Asside from that, Steve is fantastic and I hope to see more of him.

Briefing_Message: I have read the above statement
Best_Course_Features: Steve Most putting the effort in the creating high quality lectures.
Course_Improvements:
there is zero consideration for spaced repetition systems.  SRS pairs nicely with active recall (testing effect) and would be valuable for student learning.

I suggest that the psych faculty look into Anki SRS software to improve learning outcomes.
BF: Clean and straightforward lectures that get directly to the point. I have heard students say the Psychobio lectures he did are difficult, and they are, so they may just paint Denovan in a poor light due to that. You guys are probably familiar that course difficulty creates a negative bias in teacher reviews. He's a good lecturer.
IM:
Be more specific on content that isn't assessable. For example, if you include a labelled diagram of the hypothalamus, please white out labels that are not assessable, as many students may spend time learning extra information outside of the course when its not necessary. There shouldn't be any ambiguity on whether students need to learn a piece of content or not.
I do like in the neurotransmitters lecture where Denovan placed red circles around some NT's and said "these are the only ones you need to know". Do more of that, it's very helpful.

Also, like always, I recommend to every lecturer possible to incorporate spaced repetition systems in to their learning. i.e. create Anki flashcards for the course and upload them to moodle for optional use. Anki flashcards are especially useful for content such as psychobiology.
